OpenQuestions.Question: Additional information
OpenQuestions.Answer:
I was confused by the question about how many chevrutot we would like. I thought it was always one, and didn't understand how more than one would work. So my answer, "One is enough" may not be accurate.

When studying, I can get pretty excited when an observation lands on me for the first time about a particular word, passook, theme. This can come seemingly out of the blue, from the commentator I'm reading, or directly from the other person present. 

So, below, where I have not checked off "Getting inspired Jewishly," that's only because I'm already there -- in fact, on occasion, maybe I need to tone down my excitement a bit.

OpenQuestions.Answer: U.S.  SIlver Spring, Maryland (near Washington, DC)

OpenQuestions.Question: Anything else you would like to tell us
OpenQuestions.Answer:
I'm so glad there's a spot where I can mention this  -- or warn you about me :) 
Of course, discussion, debate, difference of opinion are encouraged in Jewish study. But I've also discovered that this does not apply across the board. There are just a few untouchable assumptions, and I may want to touch on one or two of them. One example where that's been expressed to me is that Esav is not a good man -- never becomes one. I'd even like to look more closely into Cain, have been wanting to for years. I guess I'll feel that out with my chevrutah.

51, Radio Producer
Before the pandemic (after my husband passed) I was attending Congregation Beth Tefillah (Scottsdale, AZ).  Before the pandemic many years ago (before my husband and I moved) I was attending shul weekly at Temple Emanuel (Tempe, AZ). 
Before meeting my husband, Jeff, I had spent 19yrs of my life vacillating whether to become a cloistered Catholic nun. Three years after meeting and dating Jeff I still felt the need to follow through and see if I had a vocation to that life and joined the Monastery of Poor Clares in Santa Barbara, CA. After being there, I realized it was not a permanent calling and left. 
My beloved and I were married a year later. I was grateful for the experience to live the monastic life as it afforded me to move forward without doubt or resentment;  for instance, there was no other place I wanted to be on my wedding day :) 
When I left the monastery, I began studying Buddhism, joined a community and eventually became ordained as one of the first 5 female priests in the Chan lineage. I was able to help others through holding a weekly meditation group practice and discussions.  Eventually, it was personally revealed to me that my teacher and his wife were using antisemitic language at a gathering where both my Jewish husband and I were attending an event. I publicly corrected my teacher and his wife and they stood by their comments.  I had another conversation privately and he again stood by the comments before becoming hostile.  Needless to say I called a formal meeting and left that teacher. 
Since my very first visit to a synagogue, I’ve felt an undeniable pull to Judaism. I was attending so regularly at Temple Emanuel that the Rabbi forgot I wasn’t Jewish. There was just a handful of us that week as there wasn’t a b’nai mitzvah, and he called me up to the bima to recite one of the blessings with the Torah already opened. The rabbi realized afterwards he had made a mistake, but I shared with him what a profound experience it was for me. It was in that moment that I knew the Torah was LIVING; not something from the past that we remember but alive here in the present.  I continued to attend weekly and began reading A Guide for the Perplexed (I think that was the title) by Maimonides. I enjoyed his writing but eventually it became very layered/complex and felt I really needed a teacher. 
It was around this time when my husband and I moved to our new home in Apache Junction. The nearest shul (would still be Temple Emanuel 30mins away or many years later I found Congregation Beth Tefillah 45mins away).
The only “formal” training I’ve had were the classes in the late 90’s leading up to our wedding in December of 2001. The classes were more of an intro (for me) and a refresher (for Jeff).
Ive been wanting to begin the path to possible conversion but due to circumstances I haven’t.  When my beloved husband passed November of 2018 I reached out to Rabbi Allouche (whom I met briefly many years before). He came to hospice at 9pm,  we said prayers and Jeff passed the next day. Once my beloved received his diagnosis 7yrs prior, we never discussed after life wishes (I absolutely don’t blame him for not wanting to talk about it).  Despite my beloved not being orthodox, I chose to have a shmirah and taharah performed along with being buried in a Jewish cemetery. 
I began attending services and events at CBT and had inquired about beginning the conversion process at that time, but learned Rabbi Allouche doesn’t perform them nor begin the process and was directed to the RCC in L.A .However, in the process of reading the paperwork, living within an erev was mandatory and something that was (and is) prohibitive for me at this time. Then the pandemic hit. 
Although, I know I’m not ready to convert at present, I would like the studying I embark on now to help me on the path of discernment. I’ve always wanted to set up a Jewish home especially when my husband and I were engaged and after we married, but I didn’t know how (I didn’t want to merely go through the actions; I wanted those actions to be the by-product of something much deeper...enriched with meaning). My husband was happy that I wanted to do so but he wasn’t raised in a religious household (he attended Hebrew school, made his bar mitzvah, and then attended shul on high holidays) and didn’t know how to help me. 
Now on my own, I’ve hung mezuzaha around the home which I find comforting and are beautiful connections and reminders for me to keep G-d always upon my lips and in my mind. 
So this is where I am right now...where would you suggest I begin? 
Baruch HaShem!
Audrey Parets
